> Today I discovered how much you can forget in a years time. Its been
> about a year since I removed the engine from my 75 bus. I took notes as
> things came apart but unfortunately the notes are nowhere to be found.:
> ( Today was going to be the day to install my new engine. The first
> problem I ran into wa the bearer bar. Forgot to bolt it to the motor
> mounts before installing the exhaust. Found out the hard way that the
> bar can be installed by removing the passenger side heat exchanger and
> raising the engine about a foot off the ground. Problem solved.
> Proceeded to try installing the engine with all the sheet metal on.
> Mistake number 2. After 2 tries I gave up because it was too cold and I
> was too frustrated to do a good job of it. While cleaning up my tools so
> I can find everything next weekend I remembered that when the engine
> came out I had to remove the tin from the rear of the engine. This was
> the only way to get that last 1/4 inch of clearance to get the lower
> engine to trans. studs to clear the holes in the bell housing. Hopefully
> this is the key to getting it back in?
> 
> Kind of bummed that the engine didn't go smoothly, but I'll try again
> next weekend. No Hurry, That's why I call it the Turtlebus. If I remove
> the sheet metal from the rear of the engine, should that give me the
> clearance I need? Should the engine be kept level with the ground or
> does it need to be tilted at all to get it in? Any advice is
> appreciated.
> 
> Sorry this is kind of long but I needed to blow off a little steam.
> 
> Thanks
> Tom
